Here is a simple JavaScript program that allows users to draw on an HTML5 canvas:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Draw on Canvas</title>
    <style>
        #canvas {
            border: 1px solid black;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="canvas" width="500" height="500"></canvas>
    <script>
        let canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');
        let ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
        let drawing = false;
        let lastX, lastY;

        canvas.addEventListener('mousedown', (e) => {
            drawing = true;
            lastX = e.offsetX;
            lastY = e.offsetY;
        });

        canvas.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
            if (drawing) {
                ctx.beginPath();
                ctx.moveTo(lastX, lastY);
                ctx.lineTo(e.offsetX, e.offsetY);
                ctx.stroke();
                lastX = e.offsetX;
                lastY = e.offsetY;
            }
        });

        canvas.addEventListener('mouseup', () => {
            drawing = false;
        });

        canvas.addEventListener('mouseout', () => {
            drawing = false;
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This program creates a canvas element and gets a reference to it using `document.getElementById('canvas')`. It then gets a 2D drawing context using `canvas.getContext('2d')`.

The program uses three event listeners to handle mouse events:

- `mousedown`: When the user clicks the mouse button, it sets `drawing` to `true` and records the current mouse position (`lastX` and `lastY`).
- `mousemove`: When the user moves the mouse while `drawing` is `true`, it draws a line from the previous mouse position (`lastX` and `lastY`) to the current mouse position (`e.offsetX` and `e.offsetY`).
- `mouseup` and `mouseout`: When the user releases the mouse button or moves the mouse out of the canvas, it sets `drawing` to `false`.

This program will allow users to draw on the canvas by clicking and dragging the mouse.

